<TITLE> DGHS reports child with bird flu </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 22 (bdnews24.com) A 16-month-old child was infected with H5N1, a deadly strain of the bird flu virus, the Directorate General of Health Services said Thursday in the first reported case. The boy, born to a Kamalapur family, recovered after 14 days of treatment. The DGHS and ICDDR,B (International Centre for Diarrhoeal Disease Research, Bangladesh) have confirmed that the child is doing well. The child was not named in the statement for the sake of privacy of his family. He was diagnosed with having the deadly virus by the US Centres for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. An advisory committee on avian influenza discussed the overall management of bird flu. Md Abul Faiz, director general of the DGHS, told bdnews24.com: "The case was spotted in January. There are many patients in our country with symptoms of flu. Under surveillance, samples have been collected from 12 hospitals." The Institute of Epidemiology Disease Control and Research and the ICDDR,B conduct the surveillance. "The sample of the H5N1 case was collected from Kamalapur. The child was suffering from acute respiratory problem. His sample was sent to Atlanta, but he was treated at home," Faiz said. The DGHS chief said there was nothing to panic. "Bird flu prevention measures are active all across the country." "It has been possible for us to identify the case because of intensified activities," he said. "Those who cull affected chickens are given medicines for seven days. They are kept under intense surveillance for 14 days," Faiz said. He said the activities had been extended to the community level. The DGHS chief said bird flu was fully under control in Bangladesh. bdnews
